It is possible that the conclusion of Europa's story loses its immediate point from our not knowing the circumstances of Galatea's Journey. Was she too, as has been suggested, to find consolation in the wealth and greatness of the com- panion of her travel? There is· no passion, though there is tenderness and kindli- ness, in the poet's feeling towards her. The Ode contrasts in this respect with the similar poems os Propertius (1. 8) and Ovid (Am. 2. 1³).

In any case Horace meant people to read his Ode who knew nothing of Galatea, and the story of Europa makes an artistic whole, even if, as is so often the case in Pindar‘s mythological episodes‚ it only touches at one point the subject with which the Ode begins.
